               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186311300100"></xptr>
               <p>about the 22d October—he had no authority whatever to receive money after he left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18631130-name-356" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18631130-name-356" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18631130-name-356" type="surname" value="SPICER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18631130-name-356" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SPICER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an oilman, at 23, Old Fish-street—I deal with Mr. Strange—on 24th October last, the prisoner called, and asked me for an account of 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and presented this bill—he said that Mr. Strange was out of town, and he asked me to give him the account, as they were out of cash—I gave him the account.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I am guilty of receiving the money, but I had no fraudulent intent. I was staying at home at the time, and I was endeavour<lb></lb>ing to obtain a situation without going home; and knowing that that money would not be called for within two or three weeks, I thought I should be able to repay it to Mr. Spicer. It is the first time anything has been said against me.</p>
